One of the direct public health risks posed by climate change is increased heat-related mortality and morbidity (
 Gosling et al. 2012; 
 Hajat et al. 2014; 
 Hales et al. 2014; 
 Kingsley et al. 2016; 
 Peng et al. 2011; 
 Petkova et al. 2013, 
 2016; 
 Sheridan et al. 2012; 
 Vardoulakis et al. 2014; 
 Wu et al. 2014) owing to increased occurrences of cardiovascular and chronic respiratory causes (
 Huynen and Martens 2015; 
 Martens 1998; 
 McMichael et al. 2006). Governments and community organizations around the world are increasingly allocating resources to prepare for a warmer future climate (
 Boeckmann and Rohn 2014). Central questions that should guide the decision-making process when making such investments include 
 a) what are the likely health impacts of possible changes, and 
 b) what are the interventions and programs, and the scale thereof, that offer the highest probability of reducing the magnitude of any adverse impacts? Answers to these questions depend in part on the extent to which populations may adapt to future climate change.
